arch:property.oc:show_val: Main construction of the Bath Complex.

Locus 27 comprises the five columns which make up the colonnade of the ‘colonnaded corridor.’ The columns are unevenly spaced, and of varying diameters, though the three to the east are all ~0.49 m in diameter and the two to the west are relatively larger. Additionally, the two west columns are at drastically different heights. Despite this, it seems that these columns were created together to form part of a colonnade which is thought to extend further to the west beyond the confines of Trench 120. The drums are hewn or dressed sandstone, some with intact plaster. The two west columns are made of three drums, the next two columns are made of two drums, and the east-most column is made of one drum. The drums have central holes for the insertion of reinforcing bars. The lack of regularity of the columns is somewhat surprising, especially given that they appear to be a rather early element of the Baths, when the quality of construction is high (when held in comparison to the later additions and reworkings which draw heavily from reused architectural elements). If the two west columns are seen as framing the stairway just to the south of it, then their larger size can be understood. All of the intercolumnar spaces were eventually blocked or narrowed (and then later blocked) to form the space for the ‘small cistern,’ the ‘bathroom,’ and the ‘anteroom.’ This locus is phased with the main construction of the Bath Complex.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.
Column #1: 1.32 m; Column #2: 1.35 m; Column #3: 0.67 m; Column #4: 1.06 m; Column #5: 0.83 m.
Column #1 (starting from the west) diameter: 0.48 m; Column #2 diameter: 0.50 m; Column #3 diameter: 0.48 m; Column #4 diameter: 0.50 m, 0.70 m at base; Column #5 diameter: 0.60 m.
